      short: [
        {q:"What are the effects of regular physical activity on the cardiovascular (circulatory) system?",a:"EFFECTS ON THE CARDIOVASCULAR SYSTEM:\n\n1. STRONGER HEART (CARDIAC HYPERTROPHY):\n• Regular exercise makes the heart walls thicker and stronger\n• Heart can pump more blood with each beat\n\n2. LOWER RESTING HEART RATE:\n• Normal resting heart rate: ~72 beats per minute\n• Athlete's resting heart rate: much lower (often 50-60 bpm)\n• More efficient heart — fulfils requirements with fewer beats\n\n3. INCREASED STROKE VOLUME:\n• More blood pumped per heartbeat\n• Greater efficiency means more oxygen delivered per stroke\n\n4. INCREASED BLOOD CELL COUNT AND HAEMOGLOBIN:\n• More red blood cells produced\n• More haemoglobin to carry oxygen to working muscles\n\n5. IMPROVED CHOLESTEROL PROFILE:\n• Decrease in LDL (bad cholesterol)\n• Increase in HDL (good cholesterol)\n• Reduces risk of coronary artery disease\n\n6. PREVENTION OF CARDIOVASCULAR DISEASES:\n• Lower risk of hypertension (high blood pressure)\n• Lower risk of heart attacks\n• Better elasticity of blood vessel walls\n\n7. IMPROVED BLOOD CIRCULATION:\n• Better capillarisation — more capillaries reach working muscles"},
        {q:"Explain the concept of 'oxygen debt' in exercise physiology.",a:"OXYGEN DEBT:\n\nDEFINITION:\nDuring vigorous exercise, when the body cannot supply oxygen fast enough to match the oxygen requirement, an 'oxygen deficit' or 'oxygen debt' is created.\n\nHOW IT OCCURS:\n• During intense exercise: muscles need large amounts of oxygen\n• Cardiovascular and respiratory systems may not be able to supply all the oxygen needed\n• Example: If athlete running needs 3 litres of oxygen per minute but lungs deliver only 2 litres — oxygen debt of 1 litre is created\n\nWHAT HAPPENS DURING OXYGEN DEBT:\n• Body switches to anaerobic metabolism\n• Lactic acid is produced as a by-product\n• Lactic acid accumulation causes muscle fatigue and burning sensation\n\nRECOVERY (REPAYING THE DEBT):\n• After exercise, breathing remains elevated\n• Extra oxygen is used to break down lactic acid\n• This continued heavy breathing after exercise = repaying oxygen debt\n\nIMPROVEMENT WITH TRAINING:\n• Regular physical training improves the body's ability to use oxygen efficiently\n• Athletes have lower oxygen debt because their cardiovascular system is more efficient\n• Recovery from exercise becomes faster with regular training"}
      ],
      long: [
        {q:"Describe the effects of regular physical activity on the muscular, respiratory, and circulatory systems.",a:"EFFECTS OF REGULAR PHYSICAL ACTIVITY:\n\nMUSCULAR SYSTEM:\n1. HYPERTROPHY: Muscles increase in size (muscle fibers thicken)\n2. INCREASED STRENGTH: More force muscles can exert\n3. IMPROVED ENDURANCE: Muscles can work longer before fatigue\n4. BETTER FLEXIBILITY: Regular stretching improves range of motion\n5. FASTER RECOVERY: Trained muscles recover faster after exercise\n6. IMPROVED COORDINATION: Better neuromuscular coordination\n7. DELAYED ONSET OF FATIGUE: Muscles use oxygen more efficiently\n\nRESPIRATORY SYSTEM:\n1. INCREASED LUNG CAPACITY: Lungs can hold more air\n2. STRONGER RESPIRATORY MUSCLES: Intercostal muscles and diaphragm strengthen\n3. IMPROVED BREATHING EFFICIENCY: More oxygen extracted per breath\n4. LOWER RESTING BREATHING RATE: Efficient lungs need fewer breaths\n5. BETTER GASEOUS EXCHANGE: Improved O₂ absorption and CO₂ elimination\n6. REDUCED OXYGEN DEBT: Better at meeting oxygen demands during exercise\n\nCIRCULATORY SYSTEM:\n1. LOWER RESTING HEART RATE: Heart works more efficiently\n2. INCREASED STROKE VOLUME: More blood per heartbeat\n3. CARDIAC HYPERTROPHY: Heart walls thicken and strengthen\n4. IMPROVED HAEMOGLOBIN LEVELS: More oxygen-carrying capacity\n5. BETTER CHOLESTEROL BALANCE: Higher HDL, lower LDL\n6. PREVENTION OF DISEASE: Lower risk of hypertension, cardiac diseases\n7. BETTER CAPILLARISATION: More capillaries reach muscles\n\nSUMMARY: Regular exercise produces lasting, beneficial adaptations in all major systems, leading to improved fitness, health and longevity."}
      ],
      passage: [
        {q:"'Regular physical activities decrease heart rate at rest in an athlete. The athlete's heart becomes so efficient that at rest same requirement is fulfilled with fewer heartbeats. Stroke volume is the quantity of blood pumped out by the aorta in one stroke. Heart, having gained efficiency with regular physical activities, is able to pump out more blood in one stroke.'\n\n(a) What is meant by 'resting heart rate'? What is the normal rate?\n(b) Why does an athlete have a lower resting heart rate?\n(c) What is stroke volume? How does training affect it?\n(d) How do these changes benefit an athlete's performance?",a:"(a) Resting heart rate is the number of times the heart beats per minute when the body is at complete rest (sitting or lying quietly, without recent exercise). Normal resting heart rate for a healthy adult is approximately 72 beats per minute (60-100 is normal range).\n\n(b) An athlete has a lower resting heart rate because:\n• Regular training causes the heart to become stronger and more efficient\n• Cardiac hypertrophy — heart walls become thicker and pump more blood per beat\n• Since more blood is pumped per beat (higher stroke volume), fewer beats are needed to circulate the same amount of blood\n• The body's oxygen requirements at rest remain the same — but the heart meets them more efficiently\n• Well-trained athletes' resting heart rate can be as low as 40-50 bpm (marathon runners, cyclists)\n\n(c) Stroke volume is the quantity of blood pumped out by the aorta (main artery from heart) in ONE BEAT/STROKE.\nEffects of training:\n• Regular physical training increases stroke volume\n• The heart's pumping chambers (ventricles) become larger and stronger\n• They can hold more blood and expel more blood per contraction\n• This means each beat is more productive — less work needed at rest\n\n(d) Benefits for athletic performance:\n• Higher stroke volume means more oxygen reaches muscles during exercise\n• Lower resting heart rate means more 'room' for heart rate to increase during exercise (greater heart rate reserve)\n• Athletes can sustain higher intensity exercise because cardiovascular system copes better\n• Faster recovery after intense exercise\n• Lower risk of cardiovascular fatigue during prolonged events"}
      ]
